<html>
<head>
 <Title>Formal Foundations of Computer Security</Title>
</head>

<body>
<h2>FORMAL FOUNDATIONS OF COMPUTER SECURITY</h2>
<p>
<HR>
<p>
This page is part of the web at the
<a href="http://www.itd.nrl.navy.mil/ITD/5540/">
 Center for High Assurance Computer Systems</a>.
<p>
<HR>
<p>
<H2>Objectives</H2>
<p>
To develop methods for evaluating security models, to develop better
security models, to develop new methods for computing covert channel
capacity, and to develop new methods for applying security models.
<p>
<ul>
  <li> Mathematical study of covert channels
       <ul>
          <li> capacity calculations
          <li> bounding techniques
          <li> effects on system performance
       </ul>
<p>
  <li> Further Development of Pump
       <ul>
          <li> secure communication moderator
          <li> allows security, reliability, and good performance
       </ul>
<p>
  <li> Formal study of selected topics in steganography and security modeling
       <ul>
          <li> Visual information hiding
          <li> Continuous capacity calculation
          <li> Composition and hook-up models
       </ul>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<H2>Recent Accomplishments</H2>
<p>

We have developed techniques for computing the capacity of
timing channels [1] and our application of these techniques to the
SINTRA database architecture [2].   We developed capacity bounds [1]
that are useful, for example, in bounding the capacity of
covert channels  arising from the need for atomicity in certain
database schedulers.  <P>

We have developed the theoretical basis of the  Pump [2] which is a dynamic,
quasi-secure, buffer
that accommodates the need for acknowledgements in communicating
computer systems.  A major benefit of the Pump is that it has minimal
negative impact upon communication throughput.  We have also extended the Pump 
to deal with a network environment [3].  We have also developed a new model 
for bursty computer communication [4] that further shows the advantages of the
Pump.
<p>
We have developed  a general theory of composition for Noninterference-like
security properties [5].  Unlike previous work, which addresses only the
question of whether a property is preserved when composed via general
hook-up with itself, we address the more general question of what
properties will be satisfied by a system in which components satisfying
different properties are composed via various types of composition
constructs.
<P>
We will study current techniques developed in steganography 
for visual information hiding and detection. 
Primarily, we are interested in the mathematical analysis of continuous
capacity calculation. We will also investigate further refinements 
 of the formal foundations of steganography.
<p>
<OL>
   <li> Moskowitz, I. and Miller, A.  "Simple Timing Channels," 
     Proceedings of 1994 IEEE Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy,
     IEEE Press, 1994.
<p>
  <li> Kang, M. and Moskowitz, I.  "A Pump for Rapid, Reliable, Secure
     Communication,"  Proceedings of the First ACM Conference on
     Computer and Communications Security," ACM Press, 1993.
<p>
   <li> Kang, M., Moskowitz, I., and Lee, D. "A network version of the Pump," 
        Proceedings of 1995 IEEE Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy,
     IEEE Press, 1995.
<p>
   <li> Moskowitz, I. and Kang, M. "The Modulated-Input Modulated-Output Model,"
       Proceedings of IFIP WG11.3 9th Conf. on database security
<p>
  <li> McLean, J.  "A General Theory of Composition for Trace Sets Closed Under
     Selective Interleaving Functions,"  Proceedings of 1994 IEEE Symposium
     on Research in Security and Privacy, IEEE Press, 1994.
</OL>
<p>
