<TITLE> Security- and Privacy-Related Standards</TITLE>
Richard Ankney (Richard.Ankney@emc2-tao.fisc.com) has graciously 
volunteered to initiate our standards coverage.  He has provided the
following outline of some security-related standards, and he plans
to flesh out these listings with descriptive paragraphs
as time permits.  This could be the start of a hypertext
document covering a wide range of security standards.
Other contributors continue to be welcome! --CEL
<HR>
<H3>Financial Industry Security Standards (ANSI X9)</H3>
<ul>
<li>X9.9:  Existing wholesale DES MAC standard
<li>X9.19: Existing retail DES MAC standard
<li>X9.23: Existing wholesale encryption standard
<li>X9.17: Existing, recently updated wholesale DES key management standard
<li>X9.24: Existing retail DES key management standard
<p>
<li>X9.30-1:  NIST DSS
<li>X9.30-2:  NIST SHA
<li>X9.30-3:  Certificate management for DSA (much new material beyond X.509)
<p>
<li>X9.31-1:  RSA signature (aligned with ISO 9796)
<li>X9.31-2:  Hash algorithms for RSA (i.e. MD2, MD5, SHA, MDC-2)
<li>X9.31-3:  Certificate management for RSA (99% same as X9.30-3)
<p>
<li>X9.41: Security Services Management
<li>X9.42: Diffie-Hellman key agreement (and variant for store and forward use)
<li>X9.44: Key transport using RSA
<li>X9.45: Authorization certificates
<li>X9.xx: Certificate extensions (also being progressed in ISO)
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>ANSI X12</H3>
<ul>
<li>X12.58 v2:  EDI Security Structures
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>IEEE</H3>
<ul>
<li>802.10c:  Key Management Protocol (used by X9.41)
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>DoD</H3>
<ul>
<li>Message Security Protocol (MSP)
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>ITU-T</H3>
<ul>
<li>X.400 (1988)
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>ASTM</H3>
<ul>
<li>E31.20:  Authentication of Electronic Health Care Information
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>Internet RFCs and Drafts</H3>
<ul>
<li>RFC 1421-1424: Privacy Enhanced Mail
<li>Draft MIME/PEM (MOSS) standards
<li>Secure HTTP
<li>Secure Socket Layer (another way to secure HTTP)
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>Cryptographic API Standards</H3>
[These are the ones of interest to X9, IEEE POSIX, NIST, and NSA]
<ul>
<li>Generic Security Services API (GSS-API)
<li>ndependent Object Protection variant of GSS-API
<li>X/Open Generic Crypto Services API
<li>RSADSI Cryptoki (PKCS #11) Abstract Token Interface API
</ul>
<HR>
<H3>RSADSI Public Key Cryptography Standards (PKCS)</H3>
<ul>
<li>PKCS #1:  RSA Encryption (and Signature)
<li>PKCS #3:  Diffie-Hellman
<li>PKCS #5:  Password-based Encryption
<li>PKCS #7:  Cryptographic Message Syntax
<li>PKCS #8:  Private Key Information Syntax
<li>PKCS #9:  Selected Attribute Syntaxes
<li>PKCS #10: Certificate Request Syntax
<li>PKCS #11: Abstract Token Interface
</ul>
<HR>
</DOC>
