<BR> <P>
<H1><A NAME="SECTION03310000000000000000">Overview of the Put Design</A></H1>
<P>
<A NAME="OverviewofthePutDesign">&#160;</A>
<P>
<TT>Put</TT> is a recursive non-terminating CSP process.  Each recurrence
chooses either to send a bit from the internal buffer, i.e., <TT>buff</TT>,
over <TT>outbit</TT> or receive a character over <TT>mid</TT>.  A bit can be
sent whenever there is one available to send; a character can be
received only if the buffer has enough room to store it.
<P>
The buffer has sufficient capacity to store a character if the buffer
is empty, since we assume <TT>buffsz &#;`\>= 1</TT>, or if <TT>buffsz*(chsz+2) &#;`\>=
(len buff)+chsz+2</TT>, since the two delimiting bits are stored along
with each <TT>chsz</TT>-length character.  Characters received are stored
at the right end of the buffer; bits transmitted are taken from the
left end of the buffer.  The design of <TT>Put</TT> in CSP follows:
<P>
<PRE>Put (chsz, buffsz, tick,buff) =
    if null buff
    then mid ? ch -&gt; Put(chsz,buffsz,tick,
                          buff ^ (startbit ]- (ch ^ .&lt;stopbit&gt;.)))
    elseif buffsz*(chsz+2) &lt; (len(buff) + chsz + 2)
    then outbit ! head(buff) -&gt; Put (chsz, buffsz, tick, tail(buff)
    else outbit ! head(buff) -&gt; Put (chsz, buffsz, tick, tail(buff)
         [] mid ? ch -&gt; Put(chsz,buffsz,tick,
                             buff ^ (startbit ]- (ch ^ .&lt;stopbit&gt;.)))
    end if</PRE>
<P>
<BR> <HR>
